the Anti-Galloway Portfolio is outperforming the Nasdaq by 8.8x and the S&P=
 500 by 12.1x over the same period.=C2=A0
Now, a few things:=C2=A0
The Prof has many more subscribers, followers, listeners, students, fans, e=
tc=E2=80=A6 than I do. He=E2=80=99s entertaining and what he=E2=80=99s doin=
g is working for him.=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s working so well that here I am highlighting his work. The iron=
y isn=E2=80=99t lost.=C2=A0
He=E2=80=99s also sold companies, served on private and public boards, is a=
 professor at NYU, and has a lot more money than I do.
He owns $10 million of Twitter stock and has been advocating that Twitter r=
eplace Jack Dorsey since he wrote a letter to the board [https://email.mg2.=
substack.com/c/eJxFkMGOhCAMhp9muK0BBMUDh73sa5gK1SGDYLCu8e2XGQ-bNG3SP-3ffg4I=
l1wuu-Wd2DuNdG1oE557RCIs7NixjMFb0UnTajUwb5UXRhsW9nEuiCuEaKkcyLZjisEBhZw-E5x=
LzZ4Wej1I0LMznOseDfDezOjmmXPXcdPfvnD4gMmhxV8sV07Ion0Sbfuj_X7InxrneTZbyfMCMe=
YTrsbltbbppPKFKR_L8wtiQfAXC1ZyKbjkRtSbRdeIxkE7edUbIVTnwChfpVl1nutJGe_FQ_F1k=
c1-TDuBe72Xs2JTpimXkJYqv56wYvwI9dOx1vVIga4RE0wR_Q2BbpYfLOOCCUtl7EegSlDIfpCq=
a3XL76crpVbKYWi7gVVnn-tU-jf9Ay3Wi_U] in December 2019.
Since he wrote that letter, the company has made none of the changes that t=
he Prof suggested. Activist hedge fund Elliott Management and less activist=
 fund Silver Lake both came in last March, though, and put Jack on a Perfor=
mance Improvement Plan. Jack passed, for now. He=E2=80=99s still the CEO. A=
nd the company=E2=80=99s stock is up 88% since Galloway=E2=80=99s letter.=
=C2=A0
Since they didn=E2=80=99t listen to him the first time, he wrote practicall=
y the same thing again last week, a year later. It=E2=80=99s worth summariz=
ing here, because it=E2=80=99s a good overview of the critics=E2=80=99 case=
 against Twitter, and of the type of lazy proposed solution that must infur=
iate the Twitter team.
Here=E2=80=99s the Prof=E2=80=99s argument against Jack and Twitter managem=
ent:=C2=A0
Twitter has underperformed the market since it went public in 2013. The Pro=
f isn=E2=80=99t wrong! Twitter=E2=80=99s performance as a public company ha=
s been uninspiring: even after its run-up over the last year, it=E2=80=99s =
up only 26% since its 2013 IPO, while social media competitors and other ma=
jor consumer(ish) tech companies have soared.=C2=A0
Source: Yahoo! Finance
Spotify, Snap, and Pinterest, which all IPO=E2=80=99d after Twitter, are up=
 87%, 165%, and 245% from their first IPO-day trade, respectively.=C2=A0=C2=
=A0
After three years in the doldrums, the Prof argues, Donald Trump saved the =
platform by winning the Presidency, and reversed the company=E2=80=99s 63% =
slide. To bolster his case, the Prof put a big fat Trump head over the 9-mo=
nth period after Trump=E2=80=99s election during which Twitter=E2=80=99s st=
ock was relatively flat. Never let the facts get in the way of a good story!
Source: No Mercy/No Malice
Rebounding because of Trump was a deal with the devil, he argues, and one T=
witter had to make because of its business model. Twitter is cool with toxi=
c content, so this argument goes, because that=E2=80=99s good for engagemen=
t which is theoretically good for Twitter=E2=80=99s ad business. The ad bus=
iness isn=E2=80=99t just bad because it encourages toxicity, though, it=E2=
=80=99s bad because Twitter isn=E2=80=99t big enough to make it work. Then =
he throws in a chart of Twitter=E2=80=99s Average Revenue Per User (ARPU) v=
ersus The New York Times, CNN, and Facebook.=C2=A0
Source: No Mercy/No Malice
Plus, now that Trump is banned, Twitter=E2=80=99s going to have problems! T=
he Prof pointed to a 5% slide when the company banned Trump, but Alex Katro=
witz points out that Banning Trump Didn=E2=80=99t Change How Much People Us=
e Twitter [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxVkE2OhCAQRk_T7DT8ibhgMZu5hkE=
olbSCgXI63n7odjGZUIHFV5VXPGcRlpQvc6SC5H2NeB1gIrzKBoiQyVkgj8EbprgWnRyIN9Iz3W=
kSyjhngN2GzWA-gRzntAVnMaT4maCUd2Q1HCjr3ay51ZopB07PvQImuJWqq-fm2tMHiA4M_EC-U=
gSymRXxKA_x9eDftaawILg1pi0tV1vOqaB1z9alvYbHu8HGGOLS1GX2o_HBR2zcauMCzZpezX66=
lQTDKWeUU83qb5hqWeusmLzsNWNSOaulr9EslafdJLX37CHpvvB_QJJNTDilXHE1fq52h-0TVAd=
jffczBrxGiHbawN968Lb8ETYuECFX-360WN0y3g9cKtEJeuuo_gTnwyDUQCrZpzoV_6C_9l6UzQ=
]. The Prof ignored the flat trading at the beginning of Trump=E2=80=99s pr=
esidency and then highlighted a quick, one-time drop as confirmatory eviden=
ce that the company is now in trouble. That=E2=80=99s narrative bias in act=
ion.
Plus, PLUS! Twitter CEO Jack Dorsey was in French Polynesia, where rich peo=
ple go =F0=9F=A4=AE, when the Capitol insurrection occurred.=C2=A0
And he speaks less than most CEOs on earnings calls (only 6% on the last on=
e), because he=E2=80=99s checked out and leads two companies (including Squ=
are, on which company=E2=80=99s earnings calls he speaks a lot more). Worse=
, and this is a good point, he thinks that Twitter should have its own paym=
ents, but that they don=E2=80=99t because Jack is conflicted thanks to Squa=
re.
All of this -- Twitter=E2=80=99s business model, Jack=E2=80=99s absenteeism=
, conflicts of interest, and a too-friendly board -- combine to not just pr=
oduce bad results, but a =E2=80=9Cthreat to the Commonwealth.=E2=80=9D=C2=
=A0
So what does the Prof think Twitter should do about it? Three things.
To learn what the Prof thinks Twitter should do, why I think he=E2=80=99s w=
rong, what I would do if I ruled the Tweets, how Twitter=E2=80=99s acquisit=
ion of Revue helps it win, and how Twitter is changing the narrative and ge=
tting its groove back=E2=80=A6=20
